Gapminder

For this assignment, we are going to use data from gapminder. Gapminder includes information about economics, population, social issues, and life expectancy from countries all over the world. We will use three data sets, so please load all three.

One thing to note is that the data include years beyond 2021. These are projections based on modeling done by the gapminder organization. Start by importing the data.

  1. (3 points) Although we can see which country has the highest life expectancy for the past 100 years, we don’t know which countries have changed the most. What are the top 5 countries that have experienced the biggest improvement in life expectancy between 1920-2020?
life_expectancy_tidy %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from=year, names_prefix="year_",values_from=life_exp) %>% 
  #avoiding issues with numeric column names
  select(country, year_1920, year_2020) %>% 
  mutate(life_change = year_2020 -  year_1920) %>% 
  arrange(desc(life_change)) %>% 
  top_n(5, life_change)
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   country         year_1920 year_2020 life_change
##   <fct>               <dbl>     <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 Kuwait               26.6      83.4        56.8
## 2 Kyrgyz Republic      16.6      73.1        56.5
## 3 Turkmenistan         15.2      70.5        55.3
## 4 South Korea          28.2      83.2        55  
## 5 Tajikistan           16.7      71          54.3
#in this case, wide format is easier to deal with.
  1. (3 points) Make a plot that shows the change over the past 100 years for the country with the biggest improvement in life expectancy. Be sure to add appropriate aesthetics to make the plot clean and clear. Once you have made the plot, do a little internet searching and see if you can discover what historical event may have contributed to this remarkable change.
life_expectancy_tidy %>% 
  filter(country=="Kuwait") %>% 
  filter(year>= 1920 & year<= 2020) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=life_exp))+geom_point()+geom_line(aes(group=1))+
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c(1920,1940,1960,1980,2000,2020))+
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title= "Kuwait Life Expectancy 1920 to 2020", x= "Year", y= "Average Life Expectancy")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1), plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.25), hjust = 0.5))

#### Apparently Kuwait’s economy collapsed in the 1920’s and 30’s, then rebounded in the 40’s as the country became more industrialized.

Population Growth

  1. (3 points) Which 5 countries have had the highest population growth over the past 100 years (1920-2020)?
population_tidy %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from= year, names_prefix= "year_", values_from= pop_size) %>% 
  select(country, year_1920, year_2020) %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth= year_2020 - year_1920) %>% 
  arrange(desc(pop_growth)) %>% 
  top_n(5, pop_growth)
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   country       year_1920  year_2020 pop_growth
##   <fct>             <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 India         317000000 1380000000 1063000000
## 2 China         472000000 1440000000  968000000
## 3 Indonesia      47300000  274000000  226700000
## 4 United States 111000000  331000000  220000000
## 5 Pakistan       21700000  221000000  199300000
  1. (4 points) Produce a plot that shows the 5 countries that have had the highest population growth over the past 100 years (1920-2020). Which countries appear to have had exponential growth?
population_tidy %>% 
  filter(country== "India"| country== "China"| country== "Indonesia"| country== "United States"| country== "Pakistan") %>% 
  filter(year>= 1920 & year<=2020) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=pop_size, group=country, color=country))+geom_point(size=.75)+ geom_line()+
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c(1920,1930,1940,1950,1960,1970,1980,1990,2000,2010,2020))+
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title="Population Growth 1920 to 2020", x= "Year", y= "Population Size", color= "Country")+
  scale_color_brewer(palette= "Paired")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.25), hjust = 0.5))

# China and India have experienced exponential growth over the past 100 years.

Income

The units used for income are gross domestic product per person adjusted for differences in purchasing power in international dollars.

  1. (4 points) As in the previous questions, which countries have experienced the biggest growth in per person GDP. Show this as a table and then plot the changes for the top 5 countries. With a bit of research, you should be able to explain the dramatic downturns of the wealthiest economies that occurred during the 1980’s.
income_tidy %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from= year, names_prefix= "year_", values_from=income) %>% 
  select(country, year_1920, year_2020) %>% #assuming that this question is also asking 1920- 2020
  mutate(gdp_growth= year_2020 - year_1920) %>% 
  arrange(desc(gdp_growth)) %>% 
  top_n(5, gdp_growth)

  1. (3 points) Create three new objects that restrict each data set (life expectancy, population, income) to the years 1920-2020. Hint: I suggest doing this with the long form of your data. Once this is done, merge all three data sets using the code I provide below. You may need to adjust the code depending on how you have named your objects. I called mine life_expectancy_100, population_100, and income_100. For some of you, learning these joins will be important for your project.

life_expectancy_100

life_expectancy_100 <- life_expectancy_tidy %>% 
  filter(year>=1920 & year<=2020)

population_100

population_100 <- population_tidy %>% 
  filter(year>=1920 & year<=2020)

income_100

income_100 <- income_tidy %>% 
  filter(year>=1920 & year<=2020)
gapminder_join <- inner_join(life_expectancy_100, population_100, by= c("country", "year"))
gapminder_join <- inner_join(gapminder_join, income_100, by= c("country", "year"))

gapminder_join %>%
